-- Arrays have value semantics under sharing: `array_set` mutates in place only
-- when the cell is uniquely owned (rc 1) and copies otherwise. With `a` still
-- live, the `array_set` that builds `b` copies, so the write is not observable
-- through `a`. This copy-on-write is what makes the type system's covariant
-- treatment of `Array` element types sound without an invariant-array rule: two
-- live aliases can never share a cell across a mutation, so you can never write
-- through one typed view and read the change back through another. Prints 0, 99.
fn main() =
  let a = array_new(3, 0)
  let b = array_set(a, 0, 99)
  println(array_get(a, 0))
  println(array_get(b, 0))
